		 <p class="contentsubhead" id="2">McubeX:</p>
		<p class="contenttext">MCubeX  is a virtual PBX system. It is hosted on the Mcube platform  and  lets you have a business phone system without having to invest in the expensive switching equipment. You have the flexibility of adding both landline and mobile numbers in the PBX. Also, since it is virtual you can have one phone system for multiple locations.</p>
		<p class="contenttext"><b>New McubeX:</b></p>
		<p class="contenttext">We can Map the assigned landing number to create new PBX system, the mapping will be taken care by our end.
		
		<img src="system/application/img/icons/newmx.png"/>
		
		</p>
		<p class="contenttext"><b>PBX Title	 :</b>  Name to identify PBX Group, you need to define a title/name of that PBX. </p> 
		<p class="contenttext"><b>PBX operator : </b> If you want the PBX to be operator driven then select an employee who will receive the calls as an operator.</p>
		<p class="contenttext"><b>PBX Greetings :</b>  Voice file to play as a greeting for incoming caller.</p>
		<p class="contenttext"><b>Landing Number : </b> The number for which this PBX is being configured.</p>
		<p class="contenttext"><b>Business Days and Hours :</b>  Configure the days and hours your business is up.</p>
		<p class="contenttext"><b>Direct Operator :</b>  It will Connect directly to operator employee.</p>
		<p class="contenttext">Once a new PBX is defined we need to add the extension numbers and the employee mapping to it.  This can be done by listing the newly defined PBX and then clicking on the  “+” icon in the “Action’ column.</p>
		<p class="contenttext">And also give the corresponding extension which can be any number which is not already in use.</p>
